<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-052-273 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 331 019</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Sept 29 1991 p5F(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Old name in televisions tries its hand with computers. (CurtisMathes Corp. developing microcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Steinert-Threlkeld, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Curtis Mathes Corp, known for its expensive high-qualitytelevision sets, is planning a line of low-cost microcomputersthrough an affiliated start-up company, Stratos Technologies Corp,doing business as Curtis Mathes Computers.andP;  To distinguish itselfin an extremely competitive business, Curtis Mathes plans to blendcomputer displays with television receivers and tuners, so thatusers can take a break from computing to watch television on theircomputer screens.andP;  In one $1,400 system, users could switch backand forth between the two, and in another more costly system, thepicture would be inset in a window, like the picture-in-picturefeature already available in many televisions.andP;  Curtis MathesComputers plans to market its computers based on a well-knownbrand name, innovative packaging, low-pricing andconsumer-friendly features instead of touting megabyte andmegahertz strength.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Curtis Mathes Corp. (Management)Stratos Technologies Corp. (Management)Curtis Mathes Computers (Product development).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersProduct DevelopmentMarketing StrategyTelevision SetsDisplaysNew Companies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>